these two methods will be called multiple times, how to fix? I only want it to be called once everytime a session is created or destroyed

To ensure that these methods are called only once when a session is created or destroyed, you can use a `ConcurrentHashMap` to store the session IDs as keys.

Here's an example to demonstrate how you can achieve this:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.ConcurrentHashMap;

// ...

public class MyHttpSessionListener implements HttpSessionListener {
    private static int onlineUserCount = 0;
    private ConcurrentHashMap<String, Boolean> sessions = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    @Override
    public void sessionCreated(HttpSessionEvent se) {
        HttpSession session = se.getSession();
        String sessionId = session.getId();

        if (!sessions.containsKey(sessionId)) {
            sessions.put(sessionId, true);
            onlineUserCount++;

            System.out.println("session created");
            ServletContext servletContext = session.getServletContext();
            servletContext.setAttribute("onlineUserCount", onlineUserCount);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void sessionDestroyed(HttpSessionEvent se) {
        HttpSession session = se.getSession();
        String sessionId = session.getId();

        if (sessions.containsKey(sessionId)) {
            sessions.remove(sessionId);
            onlineUserCount--;

            System.out.println("session destroyed");
            ServletContext servletContext = session.getServletContext();
            servletContext.setAttribute("onlineUserCount", onlineUserCount);

            System.out.println("Session destroyed for session ID: " + sessionId);
        }
    }
}
```

This will ensure that each session is only counted once in the `onlineUserCount`, and the sessionCreated and sessionDestroyed methods will only be called once per session. Note that you should remove the calls to `HttpSessionListener.super.sessionCreated(se)` and `HttpSessionListener.super.sessionDestroyed(se)` as they are not needed in this implementation.

A new session ID is generated for each new session created by a browser. If you close the browser or expire the session, the server will create a new session with a different ID when you access it again. This is normal behavior.

If you're concerned about treating multiple sessions from the same browser as one, you can use cookies to store a unique identifier for each user. This can be done by the following:

1. Create a cookie in the user's browser with a unique identifier when they first visit your site.
2. Check for the existence of this cookie when a new session is created in the `sessionCreated` method. If it exists, use the unique identifier from the cookie instead of the session ID.
3. Use that identifier as a key in the ConcurrentHashMap instead of the session ID.

Here's an example of how to achieve this:

First, you need to create a filter to create and pass the unique identifier to the HttpSession:

```java
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.Cookie;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpSession;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.UUID;

public class UserIdentifierFilter implements Filter {
    public void doFilter(ServletRequest request, ServletResponse response, FilterChain chain) throws IOException, ServletException {
        HttpServletRequest httpServletRequest = (HttpServletRequest) request;
        HttpServletResponse httpServletResponse = (HttpServletResponse) response;

        HttpSession session = httpServletRequest.getSession();
        Object userId = session.getAttribute("userId");

        if (userId == null) {
            Cookie[] cookies = httpServletRequest.getCookies();
            boolean userCookieFound = false;

            if (cookies != null) {
                for (Cookie cookie : cookies) {
                    if ("userId".equals(cookie.getName())) {
                        userId = cookie.getValue();
                        userCookieFound = true;
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }

            if (!userCookieFound) {
                userId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
                Cookie userIdCookie = new Cookie("userId", userId.toString());
                userIdCookie.setMaxAge(60 * 60 * 24 * 30); // 30 days
                httpServletResponse.addCookie(userIdCookie);
            }

            session.setAttribute("userId", userId);
        }

        chain.doFilter(request, response);
    }

    // ...
}
```

Then, update your `HttpSessionListener` to use `userId` from the HttpSession:

```java
@Override
public void sessionCreated(HttpSessionEvent se) {
    HttpSession session = se.getSession();
    String userId = (String) session.getAttribute("userId");

    if (!sessions.containsKey(userId)) {
        sessions.put(userId, true);
        onlineUserCount++;

        System.out.println("session created");
        ServletContext servletContext = session.getServletContext();
        servletContext.setAttribute("onlineUserCount", onlineUserCount);
    }
}

@Override
public void sessionDestroyed(HttpSessionEvent se) {
    HttpSession session = se.getSession();
    String userId = (String) session.getAttribute("userId");

    if (sessions.containsKey(userId)) {
        sessions.remove(userId);
        onlineUserCount--;

        System.out.println("session destroyed");
        ServletContext servletContext = session.getServletContext();
        servletContext.setAttribute("onlineUserCount", onlineUserCount);

        System.out.println("Session destroyed for user ID: " + userId);
    }
}
```

This way, even if a user accesses your site with multiple sessions or different browsers, they will still be counted as one, as long as their cookies are not cleared.

In a Java Servlet, you can get the actual IP address of a visitor using the `HttpServletRequest` object provided in the `doGet()` or `doPost()` methods. You can use the `getRemoteAddr()` method to retrieve the IP address of the client.

Here's an example:

```java
import javax.servlet.ServletException;
import javax.servlet.annotation.WebServlet;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;
import javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponse;
import java.io.IOException;

@WebServlet(name = "MyServlet", urlPatterns = {"/myservlet"})
public class MyServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {
        String ipAddress = request.getRemoteAddr();
        response.getWriter().println("Client IP address: " + ipAddress);
    }

    @Override
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            throws ServletException, IOException {
        doGet(request, response);
    }

    // ...
}
```

However, sometimes clients access your server through a proxy, load balancer, or a Content Delivery Network (CDN). In these cases, the `getRemoteAddr()` method will return the IP address of the proxy, not the actual client. To get the actual client IP in this scenario, you can look for specific headers.

For example, using the `X-Forwarded-For` header:

```java
private String getClientIpAddress(HttpServletRequest request) {
    String ipAddress = request.getHeader("X-Forwarded-For");
    if (ipAddress == null || ipAddress.isEmpty() || "unknown".equalsIgnoreCase(ipAddress)) {
        ipAddress = request.getRemoteAddr();
    } else {
        // If multiple IP addresses are present in the header, pick the first one.
        int index = ipAddress.indexOf(",");
        if (index > -1) {
            ipAddress = ipAddress.substring(0, index);
        }
    }
    return ipAddress;
}
```

With this `getClientIpAddress()` method, you can get the actual client IP address, even when your server is behind a proxy, load balancer, or CDN. Use this method to get the IP address in your `doGet()` or `doPost()` methods:

```java
@Override
protected void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
        throws ServletException, IOException {
    String ipAddress = getClientIpAddress(request);
    response.getWriter().println("Client IP address: " + ipAddress);
}
```

Keep in mind that these headers can be altered by the client and should not be relied upon for security purposes.

